Permission boundaries and delegated administration.

Here is a real problem. You want to let a developer create roles for the services they own, but you absolutely do not want them able to create a role with administrator access and then assume it. If you can grant them the power to make roles, can't they just grant themselves anything?

The answer is the permission boundary. You give the developer permission to create roles, but with a condition: every role they create must carry a specific permission boundary. That boundary caps what those new roles can ever do, no matter what permissions policy gets attached to them later.

The crucial thing to understand is that a permission boundary grants nothing on its own. It only sets a ceiling. By itself it's useless; combined with a create-role permission, it becomes the mechanism for safely handing out identity administration. You're delegating the ability to make roles without delegating the ability to escalate privilege.
